# Jobs & Events

Async side effects go through queues/schedulers — not long SMTP/S3 work on the request hot path.

## Current pattern (`NotificationsQueueService`)

```typescript
// Queue name: 'notifications'
await queue.add('order.confirmation', data, { removeOnComplete: 200, removeOnFail: 200 });
await queue.add('cart.abandonment', data, { jobId: `cart-abandon-${cartId}`, … });
await queue.add('assignment.due_reminder', data, { jobId: `article-due-${articleId}`, … });
```

Stable `jobId` ⇒ natural idempotency for that reminder/abandon event. Prefer **IDs in payload** + reload from DB over embedding mutable snapshots.

## Also async today

- `PublishingService.processDueSchedules` — flip due `SCHEDULED` → `PUBLISHED` (scanner/worker), not browser-only publish.
- Payment webhook follow-up / notifications after capture.

## Rules

| Rule | Why |
|---|---|
| Handlers idempotent | At-least-once delivery |
| Explicit retry/backoff + DLQ visibility | Ops can see poison jobs |
| Propagate `requestId` / correlation | Trace money + notify |
| Redis down ≠ corrupt stock/orders | Postgres remains source of record |
| Name jobs clearly | `order.confirmation`, `editorial.publish-scheduled`, … |

## Example domain events

`OrderPaid` · `OrderCancelled` · `ArticlePublished` · `CampaignAwarded` · `DeliverableApproved` · `PaymentCaptured`

Consumers must tolerate duplicates (same as webhook `eventId` dedupe).
